{panel:title=Atlassian Status as of 10 September 2013|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#3C78B5| titleBGColor=#3C78B5| bgColor=#E7F4FA}

Hello All, 

We're excited to announce that this improvement will be included in JIRA 6.1, so cascading select lists now support statististics.  Thanks again for your feedback and participation on this improvement request!  Keep the feedback coming!

Cheers, 

JIRA Product Management
{panel} 

\\
The statistics portlet does not allow to choose custom fields of type "cascading select lists". It would be nice to have this feature, e.g. implemented as going through all possible parent-child combinations to make it flat.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6404].
  {panel}

{panel:title=Atlassian Update - 31 March 2015|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ebf2f9 | titleBGColor=#ebf2f9 | bgColor=#ffffff}
Hi everyone,

This issue is a duplicate of JRA-12059; however, due to the high number of votes we will leave it open. Please refer to our response on that issue.

Regards,
Dave Meyer
Product Manager, JIRA Platform
{panel}

If there is a group of issue types you have to carry out for each new Version again, it's not possible to duplicate these issues with a new status for the new Version.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6395].
  {panel}

In support scenarios, it would be useful if JIRA could automatically 'escalate' issues according to defined rules (usually derived from SLA requirements).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6374].
  {panel}

I need to be able to separate admin permissions within JIRA.  For example, there is the global admin permissions which allows you to do anything in JIRA.  However, I'd like to have a permission role that would allow specified users to create new projects.  Currently, the only way to do this is to grant that user full global permissions.  We have several project managers that need to be able to create projects and be able to fully administer these projects without having global permissions.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6348].
  {panel}

When an email gets sent to a particular user (and the user is used in the "Issue Creation" service) there is no way to filter what messages will generate issues.  In particular, it would be nice if messages that were replied to (i.e. started with "Re:") did not create a new issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6324].
  {panel}

Could you enable Jira to export data in Confluence notation? At least the release notes should be something that could be just copy-pasted to Confluence.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6320].
  {panel}

Consider the following: via the web interface you add a comment to an issue and restrict the visibility of that comment to a certain group. Depending on the notification scheme in place, some individuals will get an email containing that comment. If one of those users reply to that email, that message is then viewable by all, which may or may not be expected.

What if there was an admin option to enable "plus addressing". Normally a comment would be emailed with the sender of jira@example.org. If there was this "plus addressing" option, and if a comment was created with visibility restricted to the "dev" group, then what if the sender became jira+dev@example.org? Then if a recipient replies, and assuming the JIRA email plugin knew how to parse plus addresses, this email comment would be posted with visibility restricted to the "dev" group like the original was. That way information doesn't leak out unexpectedly.

I guess an altnernative method might be to somehow contain the group info in the Subject line, as in [JIRA-1010:dev]. Though, the plus addressing seems cooler. ;-)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6314].
  {panel}

The "Assign to" field should be configurable based on the user logged in, or permission they have.  

For example, the user can only assign issues to users who are members of the same group - even though other groups have the assignable permission.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6297].
  {panel}

Manual generation of a project key is annoying.  This should be generated automatically.  Managing many projects is cumbersome when you have to generate a unique project key for each project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6265].
  {panel}

The Field Layout Scheme should allow specifying a different label for a field on a given scheme. This would allow us to create fields with usage in the title, e.g. Defect-Severity and TechCard-Severity  and have them appear as "Severity" on both screens, but with the different values specified by the custom field.

It would also allow us to change existing fields, such as "Affects Version/s" to "Proposed Fix Version", because that's how we use that field on non-defects.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6262].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6248].
  {panel}

On the Services page, a few millimeters below the frequently accessed 'Edit' link, we have 'Delete'.  Accidentally click this, and your service disappears without warning.  We should increase the visual separation between these two operations, or else add a 'Do you really want to delete?' confirmation page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6233].
  {panel}

We should have the ability to be able to create field layout schemes per component, not just per issue type.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6206].
  {panel}

It should be possible for CreateIssueHandler to handle multiple projects.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6204].
  {panel}

Given just a stacktrace of a box that is performing poorly or generating errors, it is impossible to determine the runtime state of the JIRA instance.  For instance, a CVS parse might have been running in the background creating a low memory condition, or there may have been a sudden spike in the number of users.  It would be very helpful if some vital statistics (memory, user count etc) were, eg:

2005-03-07 13:02:46,052 ERROR [core.util.thumbnail.Thumber] [510/512Mb,100u] Unable to create thumbnail image of attachment with ....

See the stat4j project (http://www.devx.com/Java/Article/22110/1954?pf=true) for some other ideas in this area.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6197].
  {panel}

It would be really nice if the user could attach a screenshot at issue creation instead of first creating the issue, refinding the issue and attaching the screenshot. It would also do away with all the "dublicate" notifications that doesn't add value.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6185].
  {panel}

We just purchased JIRA to handle our support issues, and were surprised there's no separate permissions for attachments.  Our support issues always involve binary files containing usernames and passwords.  Our customers need to be able to attach these files in order for us to solve their support problem, but, since those files contain usernames and passwords, they must not be viewable by other users.

Ideally we'd be able to configure it so that users could upload and view their own attachments, but not attachments for support issues created by others.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6169].
  {panel}

When commenting on an issue by replying to an email, security level ("Comment visible by") should be set to the same level as it was in the original mail.

Practically all email clients attach the "in reply to" mail header with original message, so it is possible to figure out which was the original comment and guess its visibility.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6163].
  {panel}

Currently, the 'Reporter' field is required by default.  When a JIRA admin the grants 'Anyone' the permission to create issues, this doesn't have the desired effect - the create issue page dies with a 'Reporter is required' error.

While we can't enforce logical consistency of admin settings, we can at least warn about likely inconsistencies such as this one.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6136].
  {panel}

We will probably end up with at least a hundred projects.  When creating a new issue, instead of having one large drop down of projects when creating an issue, can we have a project category drop down that then reduces the project drop down to those that match the category selected? Thanks.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6132].
  {panel}

I'm sure this has been filed elsewhere, but I can't find it.  A longstanding annoyance in JIRA has been how the services are scheduled to run after a *delay* instead of at a certain time each day.  This makes it impossible to schedule a backup to take place at midnight every day.  It also means that all services run when JIRA first starts up.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6123].
  {panel}

In some translations (the German translation in particular), the field names are quite long, and this makes printing issue lists difficult.  This could be fixed by providing keys for short versions of the field names to be used in column titles.  If the key value isn't found, the regular field name could be used as a fallback.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6113].
  {panel}

When specifiying a "Viewable By:" when entering the comment, the comment is displayed with the info " [21.01.2005 12:05 - Visible to jira-users]".

But, this information is not sent in the email, so the user must acutally click the issue to learn who receieved the comment and who saw it.

Please add somewhere in the mail this information. It should be very obvious (different color, bigger font, subject, something like that).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6104].
  {panel}

We currently are running on the 3.0.3 Enterprise version, and when we create release notes for our weekly patches and our other scheduled release we send out emails regrading the issues that were fixed for the patch/release.  Creating the release notes can become quite tedious because we have about 18 projects.  I suggest either have an option to create release notes (the ones that are bulleted) on a per release basis, or the improvement of allowing release notes on a per project basis.

--Jason

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6103].
  {panel}

A user has noted that a small performance gain can be made by preventing image accesses from going through the security and login filters, by customising the paths in WEB-INF/web.xml.  We should look into this (perhaps more generally, define a static/ subset of the URL space containing images, JS, css etc that can be cached).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6095].
  {panel}

Currently, a task that's created through a forwarded email comes through with a priority of Major. Most of our tasks are minor, so it would be helpful to not have to change the priority for every task that is created this way. Please provide for an optional preference where this can be changed, for each project, hopefully, but at least for each installation.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6094].
  {panel}

Currently, JIRA supports the creation of a task by an email that is forwarded to the system. Many types of embedded files, within these emails, seem to work fine, but embedded emails do not. Unfortunately, many of our forwarded emails have embedded emails within them. These are lost in the creation of the task. For reference, the file extension is a ".msg".

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6088].
  {panel}

Provide integration with jCVSWeb just like viewcvs, so users can include in cvs module information an url for jCVSWeb like view cvs, and the JIRA system provide integration to navigate at sources using jCVSWeb. The jCVSWeb site is http://www.jcvs.org/jcvsweb/ and jCVS site is http://www.jcvs.org/.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6073].
  {panel}

Currently task XML view generates XML that doesn't contain some useful information: task assign information.

Can you add this information to XML.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6036].
  {panel}

There is much wasted space on the left side of the screen in the Issue Navigator.  I would like to be able to hide the Filter information on the left side entirely.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6034].
  {panel}

Added "Description" column to the Issue Navigator, however, the column is very narrow.  There does not to be any way to change the width of the columns in the Issue Navigator.  Please advise.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6024].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-6009].
  {panel}

The POP boxes Jira reads get slowly cluttered with email that's not read in by Jira. This includes email from non-accepted email addresses and accidentally sent email. Each time jira reads through the email box, all email is scanned and for example emails from users on issues where they have no right to post result in long error log messages.

This is causing a huge amount of excess error logging in our Jira and is forcing our administrative staff to continuously manually clean up the boxes.

Could you please add a feature for Jira to purge any email boxes from the email it's been unable to read/import?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5976].
  {panel}

Please add a configuration so that anyone who "participates" in an issue (e.g., add a comment, or was assignment) is automatically on the Watch group.

Often, in our org, a bug will be reassigned, and the new assignee will make a comment expecting the last bug owner to see it, but they don't because they did not add themselves to the watch list.

It happens a lot and impacts overall productivity/throughput.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5972].
  {panel}

Trailing spaces after username when logging in are not trimmed and results in a failed login. User education _could_ fix this, but a permanent fix would be better.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5964].
  {panel}

For example, a field has a project scope appears in other fields layouts schemes that are not used by the project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5959].
  {panel}

I would like an option to "E-mail this issue" on the left side "Operations" Menu. Although I have set up notifications to notify assignees.. sometimes it would be nice to just advise a user of an issue with one click (and then e-mail to user/group).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5954].
  {panel}

Currently, after the POPService has processed an email and created an issue/comment from it, it deletes the mail.  It would be useful if JIRA could skip processed mails rather than deleting them.

This would then allow JIRA to be used as a passive recorder of the contents of a POP box, which humans are responsible for managing.  Passive support tracking would often be preferable to the current intrusive tracking; for instance, it wouldn't lose the Cc list.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5950].
  {panel}

Need a way to give users a specific number of votes.  The java.sun.com site is a good example.  A person can place all N votes on one item or spread them around.  Once an issue is closed, the votes assigned to that issue are returned the the users' pool of available votes.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5930].
  {panel}

Almost every popular search engine uses AND searches by default. This should be the default for JIRA searches, too.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5916].
  {panel}

Say one has:

      <jira:AddPermission group="Anyone" permissions="Browse"/>

This *appears* to work (in the permission scheme), but doesn't actually.  The project is still not browseable, and its issues are not visible.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5892].
  {panel}

Currently the user has to open up the issue in a browser and then click Comment on this issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5884].
  {panel}

It would be a nice feature, if it is possible to link versions. This should be possible over projects. We need this feature because our application versions (versions of application projects) base on a core version (versions of core project).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5881].
  {panel}

At this moment, if the project is finished you can leave it as is or you can delete it permanently (with or without backup it first).
It would be useful to add something like "project state" and the operation like: "inactivate" in administration secion. Then, only administrator (or someone with suitable permissions) would be able to browse the project (project invisible in "projects" element of the dashboard). Operation like "activate" would reverse the project state.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5866].
  {panel}

It would be nice to assign a common dashboard for a specific group. For example admin could configure a dashboard for the manager that get the overall statistic and developer could see the assigned to me gadget. Now the dashboard is user customizable. Every user should configure his own dashboard (which is great), but it would be interesting to set a "default" one per group of user.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5860].
  {panel}

Column headers of "change history" tab doesn't stay on "top" when sorting 

see attachements "before_sort" and "after_sort"

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5830].
  {panel}

I do not exactly know, if that is a bug or if it is volitional. An issue can be added to a released version. I think when a version is released, it is live. So no issue should be added. Is it possible to take released versions out of the fix version selection?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5816].
  {panel}

Likewise JIRA admin can send emails to selected users groups, project admin (people with administer project permissions) should be able to send custom email to project members

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5814].
  {panel}

Unless the jira-administrator group is added manually to every category of every permision scheme the account can get denied access to areas until the admin adds themself to the appropriate group.

Possible solutions are to either allow multiselection of groups when creating permission schemes or bypass security check for users in jira-admin group.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5813].
  {panel}

The ability to email a issue (attachments and all) to a outside person that does NOT have a jira user account would be extremely handy according to our developers.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5801].
  {panel}

While the searching ability is good it would be nice to be able to search on more of the predefined metadata that exists in the system such as project lead, commented by, etc.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5749].
  {panel}

currently only a JIRA Administrator can modify the list of selection parameters available for a custom field. project managers need to be able to modify the values for project-specific custom fields the same way they can modify the list of versions and components.

My apologies if this is a duplicate - I assume someone would have asked for this already but I was unable to find any related issues.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5748].
  {panel}

Our help desk uses Remedy, which is fine for immediate-attention issues.  Occasionally, a request will come through our help desk that's more of a developers issue, and in this case we'd prefer to use JIRA to track the problem.  It's no big deal to copy the information from Remedy to a JIRA issue, but it would be really cool if we could somehow use the contents of a Remedy ticket to create a new JIRA issue.

Has anyone done such work already in the form of a plugin or Remedy customization?  Wasn't able to find anything by doing some searching.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5745].
  {panel}

It would be a nice feature if the due date of the parent task was the last due date of the subtasks. This way it would be possible to get an accurate due date of the parent task without editing it every time a subtask changes.

At the least, implementing some logic to ensure that due date of subtasks cannot be set to exceed the parent task's due date would satisfy most use-cases.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5722].
  {panel}

Mailed issue template fo subtasks should show parent issue.

The mailed issue information should have *some* information about the parent. Sometimes, the subtask summary doesn't really make much sense in isolation (eg JRA-5715)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-5705].
  {panel}

I added a custom condition for making a field required at a certain step in the workflow. (the condition is that a selected field must be entered prior to executing that transition.

Unfortunately, now when the user hits the prior step and the field is blank, they simply don't see the option of executing that transition. There's no way for them to tell why.

What I'd like to see is when configuring a condition, to have the ability to type a value into a "why" field; if that field is blank (which it would be by default) everything would work as today and the user wouldn't see the transition link. If the field was populated, the transition link would appear but the field would either be disabled with hovertext containing the "why" messages collected from the various conditions that said no, or the link would be enabled but would cause a popup window with the "why" messages

